snippet.textDisplay:
You might want to see why J rubbed her but like that, I'm not a vet but if a dog does that it might be a number of things:
1. Fleas
2. Some sort of apscheas
3. Anal cancer(which might be caused by untreated apscheas)
Either way, if you notice it happening here and there, definatly go to the vet.
My dog had anal cancer and apscheas. When we found out, he was too old to go through cancer treatments so we just gave him pain killers untill it seems like it was too much so we put him down.
As for getting along with cats, I think Barbara did'nt like Fireball bc he spent a while marking her territory with his smell(from what I know lifting their tail and rubbing ont things is how cats mark terrotory). J did'nt mind bc she was'nt in her own home.
My dog was also very territorial, though he was kinda like a cat and bc he was pretty big he would have done more than just bark... There was this one cat with a death wish I would chace away from our yard at night(my perents did'nt want to let our dog inside the house).
